### Issue description

I was building with `PLATFORM_MEMORY` and I noticed when using `SetTraceLogLevel(LOG_WARNING)` I still received the following output:

```
INFO: RLSW: Software renderer initialized successfully
```

Apparently rlsw.h uses its own `SW_LOG` macro which is always enabled and simply calls `printf()`. Should rlsw.h use `TRACELOG` instead? This seems to be the behavior elsewhere (e.g. rlgl.h)

### Environment

N/A

### Issue Screenshot

N/A

### Code Example

```
#include "raylib.h"

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
	SetTraceLogLevel(LOG_WARNING);
	InitWindow(800, 450, "example");

	while(!WindowShouldClose())
	{
		BeginDrawing();

		EndDrawing();
	}

	CloseWindow();
	return 0;
}
```

### Issue description

`DrawText(int x, y)`/`DrawTextAlts...(Vector2 position)` conflates int with float.

```
void DrawText(... int posX, int posY ...);
void DrawTextEx(... Vector2 position ...);
void DrawTextPro(... Vector2 position ...);
void DrawTextCodepoint(... Vector2 position ...);
void DrawTextCodepoints(... Vector2 position ...);
```

Vector2 is eternally defined as at compatibility with:
```
typedef struct Vector2 { float x, y; } Vector2;
```

(extremely common and expectation) IEEE 754 float pair
are not
Two's complement (Universal & C23) int pair (idv. at minimum 16 bits, normally 32 bits)

This issue is most obvious in C++.

Additionally, this likely confers as a general issue with the library conflating these very different types. Regardless, float should be used unequivocally.

### Code Example
```
...
struct notavector { int x, y; };
struct notavector nv = {100, 200};
DrawText("One", nv.x, nv.y, 20, WHITE);
nv.y += 100;
// Error:
DrawTextEx(GetFontDefault(), "Two", nv /* illustrative, assume exact matching type compatibility */, 20, 0, WHITE);
// Solution:
DrawTextEx(GetFontDefault(), "Two", (Vector2) { (float) nv.x, (float) nv.y }, 20, 0, WHITE);
...
```

### Issue description
As a contiuation for #679, it would be nice to have a threadsafe raylib function that wakes the waiter up.
glfw comes with `glfwPostEmptyEvent` which corresponds to the call to `glfwWaitEvents` in `PollInputEvents`.

I'm using raylib for an desktop application where I don't want to tax the CPU if I don't have to. All my background threads for e.g. asset decoding wait on channels with shutdown messages from main. With `SUPPORT_CUSTOM_FRAME_CONTROL` I want to get radio silence if no update needs to happen.

I can work around the issue if I call `glfwPostEmptyEvent` directly. Having this in raylib would aid portability.

If you and others are interested, I can look into implementing this functionality in raylib. If not, go ahead and close this issue.

### Environment

GLFW - Wayland, Linux

### Code Example

```cpp
#include "external/glfw/include/GLFW/glfw3.h"
#include "raylib.h"
#include <chrono>
#include <print>
#include <thread>
#include <string_view>

void thrd_notifyMainAfterDelay(void);

void log(std::string_view msg) {
    auto thread_id = std::this_thread::get_id();
    auto time = std::chrono::steady_clock::now().time_since_epoch();
    std::println("[{}] [{}] {}", thread_id, time, msg);
}

int main()
{
    InitWindow(800, 450, "raylib example - basic window");

    EnableEventWaiting();

    std::thread assetThread(thrd_notifyMainAfterDelay);

    while (!WindowShouldClose())
    {
        log("Rendering on main thread!");

        BeginDrawing();
            ClearBackground(RAYWHITE);
            DrawText("Congrats! You created your first window!", 190, 200, 20, LIGHTGRAY);
        EndDrawing();
    }

    CloseWindow();

    assetThread.join();
    return 0;
}

void thrd_notifyMainAfterDelay(void) {
    using namespace std::chrono_literals;

    log("Loading asset");
    std::this_thread::sleep_for(1000ms);
    log("Finished loading asset! Handing to main thread!");
    glfwPostEmptyEvent();
}
```
